    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1669322002" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1669322002" />
    <a title="mr.fantasy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1792592-mr-fantasy"><img alt="mr.fantasy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1228952906p2/1792592.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1669322002?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="mr.fantasy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="mr.fantasy" href="/user/show/1792592-mr-fantasy">mr.fantasy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1792592-mr-fantasy?shelf=patricia-a-mckillip">patricia-a-mckillip</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1792592-mr-fantasy?shelf=fantasy-sci-fi">fantasy-sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1669322002" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11344169574160473487">Another superb Fantasy masterpiece by McKillip and all-time personal favorite. And again, as with my original notes on Forgotten Beasts (McKillip, read immediately following), too much time has passed for me to write a proper review now. But it doesn&apos;t matter as I am looking forward to waiting a bit longer to return from within the shadows for a mandatory re-read. If the concept of a fantastical medieval, coastal castle-city that has two dimensional sides, one in light (similar to our world) and</span>
  <span id="freeText11344169574160473487" style="display:none">Another superb Fantasy masterpiece by McKillip and all-time personal favorite. And again, as with my original notes on Forgotten Beasts (McKillip, read immediately following), too much time has passed for me to write a proper review now. But it doesn't matter as I am looking forward to waiting a bit longer to return from within the shadows for a mandatory re-read. If the concept of a fantastical medieval, coastal castle-city that has two dimensional sides, one in light (similar to our world) and one in shadow appeals to you, then I heavily recommend. For me it was fascinating and I enjoyed the first part of the book's challenge to visualize and tap into the city, which finally settled in comfortably near mid-book, and subsequently appeared simple in concept almost tying in syncopatically and leading towards the basic story resolution. <br /><br />The unique, light/shadow city environment I remember being perhaps one if not the strongest asset in this fairy tale. Yet, as I mentioned, much time has passed and I tend to forget favorite books and films, preserving only trace elements of their splendor(!::), so I can experience them fresh all over again a few years down the road. If I can locate my original notes regarding theme and symbolism, I'll probably append a proper, more academic review some day. From recollection, it was not that hard for me, by end and all considering, to assign this second novel by McKillip a 5-star. Great and important fantasy writer.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11344169574160473487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1669322002">
