<div id="review_3423829872" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3423829872" />
    <a title="Ben E.M." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117728946-ben-e-m"><img alt="Ben E.M." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593579112p2/117728946.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3423829872?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben E.M." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben E.M." href="/user/show/117728946-ben-e-m">Ben E.M.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117728946-ben-e-m?shelf=fairy-tales">fairy-tales</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117728946-ben-e-m?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3423829872" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15644107366461456543">Despite my two star rating, this is not a bad book. I don&apos;t have any issues with it in an objective sense—I just happened not to enjoy it. <br/><br/>It&apos;s an extremely gentle read. While the story contains tragic, violent, and desperate events, McKillip writes in a way that papers over the intensity of these inherently terrible things. As a result, the book felt a bit like a fairy tale (although there weren&apos;t any actual fairies). Think Rapunzel, which, at it&apos;s heart is a tale about a stolen child locked in</span>
  <span id="freeText15644107366461456543" style="display:none">Despite my two star rating, this is not a bad book. I don't have any issues with it in an objective sense—I just happened not to enjoy it. <br /><br />It's an extremely gentle read. While the story contains tragic, violent, and desperate events, McKillip writes in a way that papers over the intensity of these inherently terrible things. As a result, the book felt a bit like a fairy tale (although there weren't any actual fairies). Think Rapunzel, which, at it's heart is a tale about a stolen child locked in a tower. It's a horrible situation, but the story is typically told in a gentle and mild way.<br /><br />This is not a flaw, just a stylistic choice that happened not to work for me. I prefer when authors lean in to the intensity of their tales; I want to feel like I am sharing the characters' experiences, good and bad.<br /><br />I should note that the prose is really nice. McKillip writes an excellent sentence, and I finished the book on the strength of her writing despite never feeling connected to the characters or story. <br /><br />Four stars for craft, but two for my own enjoyment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15644107366461456543" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

